For a central quadric $v^\top S v=-J$ with symmetric $3\times3$ matrix $S$, a rotation diagonalizes it to $\lambda_1X^2+\lambda_2Y^2+\lambda_3Z^2=\mu$. The eigenvalue signs classify it:
- all same sign as $\mu$: **ellipsoid** (sphere if all equal);
- two positive, one negative (with $\mu\neq0$): **hyperboloid of one sheet** if one eigenvalue opposes $\mu$, two sheets if two oppose it;
- mixed signs with $\mu=0$: a **cone**;
- one eigenvalue zero (rank drop): **cylinder** or **paraboloid** depending on the linear part.
The $4\times4$ matrix $A$ (full coefficients) and its $3\times3$ block $B$ play the roles of $A_{33}$ and $A_{22}$: $\operatorname{rk}A$ tells degenerate vs proper, and the eigenvalue signs of $B$ give the shape.
